UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780197687925.003.0004
AU  - John A. Nyman
AB  - Abstract
               In this chapter, the history of the development of the insurance and gambling industries is reviewed. The history of these industries is revealing because it shows how early firms adopted behaviors consistent with the concepts of probability and the law of large numbers, many years before these concepts were formally described by mathematicians. The story of the mathematicians who first wrote about and popularized these concepts is then also presented. The chapter ends with a discussion of the motivations of these firms. It argues that, even though measures were commonly taken in both these industries to reduce risk, any businessman or woman who owned a firm in these very risky businesses could hardly ever be regarded as being adverse to risk.
