UR  - https://doi.org/10.1093/oso/9780197687925.003.0002
AU  - John A. Nyman
AB  - Abstract
               This chapter presents the conventional theory of the demand for insurance and compares it to the quid pro quo theory. It shows how, with the same assumptions, the quid pro quo analysis of demand would lead to the same welfare gain as the conventional theory. It then shows how the conclusion from conventional theory that demanders of insurance seek certainty has led economists to ignore five important welfare gains from insurance. These gains are captured by the quid pro quo theory and change the nature of the policy issues and prescriptions. The chapter ends with a digression on how the decomposition of quantity demanded from a price reduction generated by coinsurance differs from the decomposition generated by an exogenous drop in the market price. It begins with a review of the origins of the concept of utility and of utility functions that are increasing with income at a decreasing rate.
