TI  - Crisis Sentiment in the U.S. Insurance Sector
JO  - Journal of Risk and Insurance
PY  - 2016
DO  - 10.1111/jori.12156
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jori.12156
AU  - Felix Irresberger
AU  - Fee Elisabeth König
AU  - Gregor N. F. Weiß
AB  - AbstractWe use Internet search volume data to measure idiosyncratic and market‐wide crisis sentiment to explain insurer stock return volatility. We find that market‐level crisis sentiment was a significant predictor of stock return volatility of U.S. insurers between 2006 and 2010. Higher levels of crisis sentiment are associated with higher levels of price uncertainty. This effect is strongest for insurers with less exposure to the adverse effects of the financial crisis. Further, crisis sentiment also affects the cross‐section of movements in insurer stock prices. Our results imply that investors exited insurer stocks mainly due to crisis sentiment rather than a rational assessment of the insurers’ actual exposure to the crisis.
ER  - 

