TI  - Enterprise Risk Management and Default Risk: Evidence from the Banking Industry
JO  - Journal of Risk and Insurance
PY  - 2016
DO  - 10.1111/jori.12151
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/jori.12151
AU  - Sara A. Lundqvist
AU  - Anders Vilhelmsson
AB  - ABSTRACTEnterprise risk management (ERM) has emerged as a framework for more holistic and integrated risk management with an emphasis on enhanced governance of the risk management system. ERM should theoretically reduce the volatility of cash flows, agency risk, and information risk—ultimately reducing a firm's default risk. We empirically investigate the relationship between the degree of ERM implementation and default risk in a panel data set covering 78 of the world's largest banks. We create a novel measure of the degree of ERM implementation. We find that a higher degree of ERM implementation is negatively related to the credit default swap (CDS) spread of a bank. When a rich set of control variables and fixed effects are included, a one‐standard‐deviation increase in the degree of ERM implementation decreases CDS spreads by 21 basis points. The degree of ERM implementation is, however, not a significant determinant of credit ratings when controls for corporate governance are included.
