AB  - AbstractRisk sharing in insurance is analyzed, with a view toward explaining the prevalence of deductibles.First we introduce, in a modern setting, the main concepts of the theory of risk sharing in a group of agents. We apply this theory to the risk‐sharing problem between an insurer and an insurance customer. We develop the concept further through simple examples, illustrating some of the subtle points of this theory.To deduce deductibles endogenously, not explained in the neoclassical model, we separately introduce (a) the insurable asset as a decision variable, (b) administrative costs, and (c) moral hazard, and illustrate these with the help of examples.
