TY  - GEN
TI  - <scp>Market Risk, Interest Rate Risk, and Interdependencies in Insurer Stock Returns: A System‐GARCH Model</scp>
JO  - Journal of Risk and Insurance
PY  - 2008
DO  - 10.1111/j.1539-6975.2008.00289.x
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1539-6975.2008.00289.x
AU  - James M. Carson
AU  - Elyas Elyasiani
AU  - Iqbal Mansur
AB  - AbstractWe examine market risk, interest rate risk, and interdependencies in returns and return volatilities across three insurer segments within a System‐GARCH framework. Three main results are obtained: market risk is greatest for accident and health (A&amp;H) insurers, followed by life (Life) and property and casualty (P&amp;C) insurers; interest rate sensitivity is negative and greatest for Life insurers; and interdependencies in returns are significant with the magnitude being strongest between P&amp;C and A&amp;H insurers. The implication is that greatest diversification benefits arise between Life and the other segments of the insurance industry. Market risk and interest rate risk for diversified firms are smaller than those for nondiversified firms for both product and geographic diversification.
ER  - 

TY  - GEN
TI  - Optimal Risk‐Sharing and Deductibles in Insurance
JO  - Encyclopedia of Quantitative Risk Analysis and Assessment
PY  - 2008
DO  - 10.1002/9780470061596.risk0361
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1002/9780470061596.risk0361
AU  - Knut K. Aase
AB  - Abstract
          Risk sharing in insurance is analyzed, with a view toward explaining the prevalence of deductibles.
          First we introduce, in a modern setting, the main concepts of the theory of risk sharing in a group of agents. We apply this theory to the risk‐sharing problem between an insurer and an insurance customer. We develop the concept further through simple examples, illustrating some of the subtle points of this theory.
          To deduce deductibles endogenously, not explained in the neoclassical model, we separately introduce (a) the insurable asset as a decision variable, (b) administrative costs, and (c) moral hazard, and illustrate these with the help of examples.
ER  - 

