TY  - GEN
TI  - <scp>Homeowners Insurance With Bundled Catastrophe Coverage</scp>
JO  - Journal of Risk and Insurance
PY  - 2004
DO  - 10.1111/j.0022-4367.2004.00094.x
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.0022-4367.2004.00094.x
AU  - Martin F. Grace
AU  - Robert W. Klein
AU  - Paul R. Kleindorfer
AB  - AbstractWe estimate the demand for homeowners insurance in Florida and New York with indicated loss costs as our proxy for the quantity of real insurance services demanded. We decompose the demand into the demand for coverage of catastrophe perils and the demand for noncatastrophe coverage and estimate these demand functions separately. Our results are relatively consistent in New York and Florida, including evidence that catastrophe demand is more price elastic than noncatastrophe demand. We also find evidence that consumers value options that expand coverage, buy more insurance when it is subsidized through regulatory price constraints, and consider state guaranty fund provisions when purchasing insurance.
ER  - 

TY  - GEN
TI  - Asymmetric Information Problems in Taiwan's Automobile Insurance Market: The Effect of Policy Design on Loss Characteristics
JO  - Risk Management and Insurance Review
PY  - 2004
DO  - 10.1111/j.1098-1616.2004.00036.x
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1098-1616.2004.00036.x
AU  - Jennifer L. Wang
AB  - AbstractThis article investigates asymmetric information problems for the automobile insurance market in Taiwan. Using panel data for the comprehensive automobile insurance coverage from 1995 to 1999, this article analyzes how types of coverage, deductible amounts, and experience ratings have affected the adverse selection and moral hazard problems in Taiwan's automobile insurance market. The empirical results provide partial evidence to demonstrate that the loss frequency and loss ratio were reduced by the addition of self‐selection mechanisms in policies with different levels of coverage. In addition, the deductible amounts, experience ratings, and better control of underwriting and claims processing were shown possibly to have decreased potential losses from adverse selection and moral hazard problems.
ER  - 

